        <p>The highlight is the <italic toggle="yes">O. sativa</italic> model, which presented 57.0% and 52.5% of the predictions of the TSS signal with an error smaller than 50 nt in <italic toggle="yes">A. thaliana</italic> and <italic toggle="yes">Z mays</italic>; respectively. This performance is equal the result observed in the <italic toggle="yes">O. sativa</italic> model performed in the cross-validation process (intra-species).</p>
        <p>For the <italic toggle="yes">C. familiaris</italic> predictions using the <italic toggle="yes">H. sapiens</italic> model, the result was surprising: accuracy measures were superior to those obtained in the <italic toggle="yes">H. sapiens</italic> cross-validation experiments in all distance thresholds, with F1-score values ranging from 50.8% to 80.9% versus 34.3% to 72.1%.</p>
